lt has generally been supposed that the antiquarian · poems of the Fourth Book—the first, second, fourth, ninth and tenth—were written in the poet's first youth, and before the Cynthia period of his lif . But there is no proof for this hypothesis3 nor is it supported by any evidence to be extracted from the poems themselves Alike in sub· ject and in treatment they display a calmness and a continuity altogether foreign to the rapid fervour and exuberant passionateness of the poet‘s earliest days, they seem a very fulfilment of the poet’s own promise in 3. 5. 19 sqq, that while devoted to Love and Bacchus in his hot youth, he will turn, with advancing age, to graver themes. Now had Propertius turned to antiquarian sub- jects in his youth, we may be certain that he would have gone to the mythology of Greece for his subject.
